(version 1)
;; ===========================================================================================
;; @piflow/core SeatbeltSandbox READ-SCOPE profile -- macOS Seatbelt (sandbox-exec).
;;
;; This is the @piflow/core port of templates/pi-runner/sandbox/read-scope.sb. The SeatbeltSandbox
;; provider (sandbox/seatbelt.ts buildSandboxProfile) renders a per-exec copy of this template with
;; the home, tmpdir, and declared-scope tokens substituted, then runs sandbox-exec -f <copy> sh -c <cmd>.
;;
;; Two hard rules for editing this file (DO NOT BREAK THEM):
;;   1. Comments are PURE ASCII. The SBPL/TinyScheme reader miscounts multibyte UTF-8 (em-dashes,
;;      ellipses) and then parses comment text as code (an "unbound variable" error).
;;   2. NEVER write a driver placeholder token in a comment. The provider string-substitutes those
;;      tokens; a multi-line scope value spilled into a comment becomes live code and breaks parsing.
;;      Each token below appears ONCE, only at its rule site.
;;
;; WHY: a non-Claude model ignores a prompt-level READING LAW and spelunks files outside its lane (it
;; grepped the whole repo for a phantom component and read other units source, bloating context, then
;; stalled). Prompt rules are unenforceable on weak models, so the scope boundary must live in the OS.
;; Seatbelt is kernel-enforced, INHERITS to every child process (so a spawned grep/find/cat is bound
;; too) and cannot be lifted from inside the sandbox.
;;
;; POLICY: allow everything EXCEPT file reads; deny ALL file reads; then re-allow exactly (1) the
;; toolchain/system roots a node + node + npm need to run and (2) the per-exec DECLARED scope the
;; provider injects below. A read of the wider tree (another unit, or a grep from the filesystem root)
;; returns Operation-not-permitted, while the workdir, the declared read scope, and node_modules read fine.
;;
;; SCOPE: reads only (the incident was a read-scope failure). exec and network are left open (allow
;; default) so the toolchain is unaffected; tighten those later if wanted.
;; ===========================================================================================

(allow default)

;; Deny every file read up front, then immediately re-allow METADATA everywhere (last match wins).
;; Metadata = stat/traverse, which the toolchain needs to resolve paths (node getcwd / dyld); denying
;; it EPERMs uv_cwd and node never boots. DATA (content) stays denied globally and is re-granted only
;; for the scoped subpaths below -- and content is exactly what a wandering read leaks: cat/grep read
;; file data, ls/find readdir reads directory data, so both stay blocked for out-of-scope paths.
(deny file-read*)
(allow file-read-metadata)

;; --- toolchain / system roots: node, npm, the dyld shared cache, temp ---
(allow file-read*
  (subpath "/usr")
  (subpath "/bin")
  (subpath "/sbin")
  (subpath "/System")
  (subpath "/Library")
  (subpath "/opt")
  (subpath "/private/var")
  (subpath "/private/tmp")
  (subpath "/private/etc")
  (subpath "/dev")
  (subpath "@TMPDIR@")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.pi")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.npm")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.cache")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.config")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.nvm")
  (literal "/")
  (literal "/etc")
  (literal "/tmp")
  (literal "/var"))

;; --- per-exec DECLARED read scope (provider-injected from CreateOpts.readScope + the workdir) ---
;; the node's workdir + its declared read roots + node_modules. Anything not listed here (sibling
;; units, other out dirs, the wider repo) stays denied.
(allow file-read*
@SCOPE_ALLOWS@)
